    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-03-14T21:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-03-14T21:25:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <head>243. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in France</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d243fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 700.5612/3–1462. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_FR1"
                            >Fessenden</persName>; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_TWR1"
                            >Tyler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OHD1">Owen</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BEJ1">Beigel</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BM2">Bundy</persName> (in substance); and approved and
                        signed by Ball.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-14T21:25:00-05:00">March 14, 1962, 9:25 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4920. Eyes only from Acting Secretary for Ambassador. Our relations with the
                    French on nuclear questions are obviously at a very low ebb. This has been made
                    clear by your recent conversations with <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >Debre</persName> and others, and by <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >Debre</persName>’s remarks to the American correspondents. The bitterness
                    shown by the French on this subject makes it plain that very little can be
                    gained by discussing the subject further with the French at this time.</p>
                <p>The President believes therefore that it would be best for the present to avoid
                    being drawn into further discussion of nuclear questions with French officials
                    which could only further exacerbate our bilateral relations generally.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Ball</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
